But, first, a battle is brewing
over proposed rules about the
advice that financial advisers

23:11.523 --> 23:14.560 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
can give their customers.

23:14.560 --> 23:19.665 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The fight is one of several big
dividing lines this week on
Capitol Hill, and it's spilled

23:19.665 --> 23:25.070 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
into the spending standoff as
well. The deadline to pass a new
spending bill is tomorrow.

23:25.070 --> 23:27.840 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
William Brangham has been
speaking with several of the key
players as we get closer to the

23:27.840 --> 23:30.776 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
deadline, and he joins me now.

23:30.776 --> 23:33.445 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, this has finally percolated
its way to Congress, but what is
at the root of this

23:33.445 --> 23:35.981 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
dispute, William?

23:35.981 --> 23:37.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The root of
this dispute is that the
Department of Labor wants to
change

23:37.916 --> 23:41.587 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the rules governing
retirement advisers.

23:41.587 --> 23:45.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And these are people you go to
if you need help with your
401(k) or rolling over your

23:45.624 --> 23:49.528 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
IRA, things like that. And the
Department of Labor wants to
change it so that all these

23:49.528 --> 23:54.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
advisers have to have what is
called the best interests of
their client at heart.

23:54.566 --> 23:58.137 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, many of us might think,
well, doesn't my adviser already
have my best interest at

23:58.137 --> 24:01.106 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
heart? And most of them do, but
not all of them, and not all of
them are legally required

24:01.106 --> 24:03.509 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to do so.

24:03.509 --> 24:08.714 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, that can sometimes mean that
you might get sold a plan that
has a lot of higher fees

24:08.714 --> 24:12.685 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that is maybe not the best plan
for your retirement future. And
so the Department of Labor wants

24:12.685 --> 24:18.590 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to say, OK, put your clients'
interests ahead of you, ahead of
your own across the board.

24:18.590 --> 24:20.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, yesterday, I talked to the
labor secretary, Thomas Perez,
and here's what he had to say

24:20.626 --> 24:22.661 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
about this.

24:22.661 --> 24:27.499 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
THOMAS PEREZ, U.S. Secretary of
Labor: This is not a case of
people with malice in their

24:27.499 --> 24:33.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
heart who are trying to screw
people. This is a case about a
system that's structurally

24:33.038 --> 24:35.240 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
flawed.

24:35.240 --> 24:41.947 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The incentives are misaligned.
Under the current standard,
which is a so-called suitability

24:41.947 --> 24:48.354 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
standard, I can have four or
five different products that are
so-called suitable for you.

24:48.354 --> 24:55.094 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what happens? Well, the
product that generates the most
commission for the salesperson
is

24:55.094 --> 24:58.030 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
the product that
invariably gets sold.

24:58.030 --> 25:02.701 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so the consumer loses,
and the salesperson wins.

25:02.701 --> 25:06.004 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: So, William, the
consumer loses and the
salesperson wins, as Secretary
Perez

25:06.004 --> 25:09.007 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
says. How much money are
we talking about here?

25:09.007 --> 25:12.945 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The White
House estimates that $17 billion
is lost every single year

25:12.945 --> 25:18.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by advisers who are getting what
they call this conflicted
advice, where you're sold

25:18.117 --> 25:20.319 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
something where the fees are
higher than they should be or
that is just not the optimal

25:20.319 --> 25:23.222 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
plan for you.

25:23.222 --> 25:28.227 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the complicated issue here
is that there is a dizzying
array of retirement options

25:28.227 --> 25:30.229 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
out there. And it's very
difficult for people to know
where to turn, so naturally they
seek

25:30.229 --> 25:32.498 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
advice.

25:32.498 --> 25:35.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of the advocates that I
spoke with likened this to when
you're driving down the road

25:35.200 --> 25:37.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in your car, and, all of a
sudden, you hear a big bang
coming out of your engine. You

25:37.936 --> 25:40.606 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
take it to one mechanic and he
says, that's $1,500 because you
have got to replace your

25:40.606 --> 25:41.907 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
transmission.

25:41.907 --> 25:46.512 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Take it to another mechanic, he
says, oh, it's $1.99 for a spark
plug.

25:46.512 --> 25:51.183 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Unless you're an auto mechanic,
you just don't know, well, who's
right and who's wrong. And

25:51.183 --> 25:54.953 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
some of the advocates argue that
financial advice is the same
way.

25:54.953 --> 25:58.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Dennis Kelleher, the CEO of an
advocacy group called Better
Markets, put this way.

25:58.690 --> 26:01.193 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DENNIS KELLEHER, President,
Better Markets: So, it's
perfectly reasonable to get
advice

26:01.193 --> 26:05.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for such complex matters. The
problem is that it's not
transparent.

26:05.964 --> 26:10.269 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You -- the person doesn't know,
what are the 20 or 30 different
types of products available?

26:10.269 --> 26:15.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What are the fees? How do they
perform over time? And am I
getting a high-cost product

26:15.941 --> 26:20.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that's going to perform poorly
or a low-cost product that will
perform better? And you

26:20.112 --> 26:22.781 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are never going to know because
you never see the alternative.

26:22.781 --> 26:26.785 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: The industry
obviously is not taking this
lying down. They are going to

26:26.785 --> 26:29.855 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
continue to fight this, and
they're spending a lot of money
on it.

26:29.855 --> 26:32.391 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The industry
has spent already millions of
dollars trying to torpedo these

26:32.391 --> 26:34.827 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
rules.

26:34.827 --> 26:39.298 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They put a rider in the current
omnibus spending bill that is
going to try to eliminate the

26:39.298 --> 26:44.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ability of the Department of
Labor to introduce this, and
they are arguing that these
rules

26:44.937 --> 26:47.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are unnecessary, that they're
going to overly burden the
industry, people will not get
the

26:47.840 --> 26:51.743 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
advice that they need, and that
this is just an unnecessary set
of rules.

26:51.743 --> 26:55.047 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: You talked to Kevin
Mayeux, the National Association
of Insurance and Financial

26:55.047 --> 26:57.716 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Advisers spokesmen. Let's
hear what he said.

26:57.716 --> 26:59.751 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
KEVIN MAYEUX, National
Association of Insurance and
Financial Advisers: Financial
advisers

26:59.751 --> 27:02.888 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
that are successful are
constantly acting in the best
interests of their clients,
because,

27:02.888 --> 27:06.024 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
if they weren't, they wouldn't
be in business anymore.

27:06.024 --> 27:10.262 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
There is already ample
opportunity to discipline bad
actors. And the cost of the
complying

27:10.262 --> 27:15.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
with a complex federal
regulation that is 1,000 pages
in length is just going to make

27:15.033 --> 27:19.805 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it prohibitive for companies to
put their advisers on the street
to help clients and

27:19.805 --> 27:22.241 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for advisers to be able to
access clients to give them an
array of options from which

27:22.241 --> 27:24.209 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
they can choose.

27:24.209 --> 27:27.079 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: When the industry
talks about the cost of
compliance, how burdensome are

27:27.079 --> 27:29.748 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
they saying these
regulations would be?

27:29.748 --> 27:33.585 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: They say that
they are very burdensome. They
say this is 1,000 pages of

27:33.585 --> 27:37.256 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
regulations, and maybe big firms
can handle the compliance costs
of that, but smaller

27:37.256 --> 27:39.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
advisers can't, and that some of
those advisers might look at
this and say, I'm getting out

27:39.291 --> 27:41.260 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of this business.

27:41.260 --> 27:44.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: So, what do you if
you're something who is just
depending on your financial
adviser

27:44.997 --> 27:48.267 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to handle your nest egg?
What do you do now?

27:48.267 --> 27:49.868 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Well, if you
really want to know whether or
not they're looking out

27:49.868 --> 27:52.671 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for you, you can ask.

27:52.671 --> 27:56.642 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's an awkward conversation,
but you can literally say to
your adviser, do you have

27:56.642 --> 28:00.879 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the legal obligation to look out
for my best interests? Now, if
they say, I don't have

28:00.879 --> 28:04.816 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the legal obligation, it doesn't
mean they are going to try
swindle you necessarily.

28:04.816 --> 28:07.953 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But if they say they do have
that obligation, then chances
are you can be more comfortable

28:07.953 --> 28:12.691 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with that. But if you already
have a plan, and you're
wondering, was this a good plan,

28:12.691 --> 28:16.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
did I get sold a bill of goods,
you can take it to someone like
a certified financial planner

28:16.995 --> 28:21.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or a registered financial
adviser, people who do have that
legal obligation, and say,

28:21.800 --> 28:24.303 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
review this for me. Tell me, is
this a good plan for me or not?

28:24.303 --> 28:25.604 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: William Brangham,
thank you very much.

28:25.604 --> 28:31.276 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Thank you.

28:31.276 --> 28:43.155 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Newsrooms across the
country have long been accused
of failing to represent

28:43.155 --> 28:47.559 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the communities they cover. And
as racial concerns continue to
rise to the surface across

28:47.559 --> 28:51.697 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the country, who is
telling those stories?

28:51.697 --> 28:55.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's the question being raised
by one group of journalists, and
the topic of the latest

28:55.400 --> 28:58.971 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
installment of special
correspondent Charlayne
Hunter-Gault's solutions-based
series "Race

28:58.971 --> 29:00.839 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Matters."

29:00.839 --> 29:07.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: Race
nowadays is all over the news
media, not at least coverage

29:07.846 --> 29:12.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of protests in places like
Ferguson, Baltimore and New
York.

29:12.117 --> 29:17.422 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the media are also taking
hits from critics, especially
those who complain of a lack of

29:17.422 --> 29:23.929 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
fairness or consistency, again,
when it comes to issues
involving race.

29:23.929 --> 29:29.334 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Richard Prince is a journalist
focusing on race and diversity
in his thrice-weekly online

29:29.334 --> 29:35.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
column "Journalism." It runs on
the Web site of the Maynard
Institute, the sponsoring
organization

29:35.340 --> 29:40.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
started in the wake of the
mid-'60s riots and aimed at
trying to correct the lack of

29:40.379 --> 29:44.583 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
stories relating to
race and diversity.

29:44.583 --> 29:50.722 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We met Prince at the Newseum, a
Washington, D.C.-based
institution that's home to
examples

29:50.722 --> 29:56.194 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of media committed to fairness
and balance in their coverage of
race and diversity.

29:56.194 --> 29:57.796 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Richard Prince, thank
you for joining us.

29:57.796 --> 29:59.431 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
RICHARD PRINCE, The Maynard
Institute: So glad to be here.

29:59.431 --> 30:03.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: Your
column carries a lot of articles
about journalists who are

30:03.969 --> 30:09.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
themselves complaining about
fairness in media. What's your
take on the criticisms of media

30:09.408 --> 30:12.010 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and their issues?

30:12.010 --> 30:15.113 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD PRINCE: I don't think
there is any more criticism of
the media than there has

30:15.113 --> 30:18.717 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ever been. It's just that we get
to hear it now and see it
instantaneously.

30:18.717 --> 30:23.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: Well,
you're a little younger than I
am, but I remember the
presidential

30:23.188 --> 30:30.595 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
commission that reported on the
riots in the mid-'60s. And it
blamed the media for not

30:30.595 --> 30:35.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
having enough people or any
people at all in the
neighborhoods where people were
simmering

30:35.600 --> 30:44.076 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
over few -- lack of jobs, poor
education, no opportunities.

30:44.076 --> 30:47.779 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it said that you have got to
get more African-Americans or
people from those neighborhoods

30:47.779 --> 30:48.747 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the media.

30:48.747 --> 30:50.482 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What happened?

30:50.482 --> 30:53.018 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD PRINCE: Well, since that
time, there was a great push, as
you say, after the Kerner

30:53.018 --> 30:55.854 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Commission report of 1968.

30:55.854 --> 31:02.027 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All through the '70s, diversity
was a great buzzword. And then
in the '80s, you started

31:02.027 --> 31:08.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
getting a backlash to
affirmative action and that kind
of thing. Then you had the
recession,

31:08.133 --> 31:12.270 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which meant that newsrooms had
to sort of tighten up and not
hire as many people, start

31:12.270 --> 31:15.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
laying people off, and the
Internet, which made things
worse, because it took away a

31:15.474 --> 31:19.911 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
lot of the revenue base of
newspapers particularly.

31:19.911 --> 31:27.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so diversity sort of went
off the table. And so now we are
sort of in a stagnant situation,

31:27.419 --> 31:32.624 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
where the -- I think of
newspapers, for example, and
online outlets. We have 13
percent of

31:32.624 --> 31:37.229 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the newsrooms now are people of
color, whereas the population
has a third people of color.

31:37.229 --> 31:39.898 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So there's a big gap there.

31:39.898 --> 31:45.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: So there
continues to be this black-white
divide in racial discourse.

31:45.103 --> 31:48.240 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
How much of that is the
fault of the media?

31:48.240 --> 31:52.844 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD PRINCE: Well, of course,
one of the purposes of the news
media, and particularly

31:52.844 --> 31:55.747 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of newspapers and local
television stations, is to have
different parts of the community

31:55.747 --> 31:58.283 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
talking with each other.

31:58.283 --> 32:03.288 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think there are a lot of news
organizations that do take that
role very seriously, less

32:03.288 --> 32:09.294 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so with others. It also depends
on the staff you have and how
aggressive they are in demanding

32:09.294 --> 32:13.165 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of their editors that
certain things be covered.

32:13.165 --> 32:19.271 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, logically, the more people
you have of color there, or
good-thinking people who are

32:19.271 --> 32:22.808 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
not of color, the better
the coverage will be.

32:22.808 --> 32:25.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: But are
we losing people of color as the
-- as you have the

32:25.777 --> 32:27.212 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
consolidation of media?

32:27.212 --> 32:29.314 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
RICHARD PRINCE: Yes.

32:29.314 --> 32:32.050 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: And
what's going to be the result of
that?

32:32.050 --> 32:35.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD PRINCE: Well, because of
all the layoffs and buyouts and
everything, that
African-American

32:35.654 --> 32:39.958 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
journalists particularly have
been harder-hit than others.

32:39.958 --> 32:46.498 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, you know, covering people
of color and communities of
color is not just the
responsibility

32:46.498 --> 32:50.836 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the journalists of color on
the staff. It's everyone's
responsibility. So, if you

32:50.836 --> 32:57.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have people, white people, white
journalists who care about this
issue, then it will get

32:57.709 --> 32:59.878 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
done.

32:59.878 --> 33:03.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we have -- saw a good
example of that, and when a
crisis happens such as in
Charleston,

33:03.715 --> 33:08.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
South Carolina, with the church
shooting, where that newspaper
there had actually decreased

33:08.053 --> 33:12.224 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in diversity, but they still did
a good job, according to most
estimates, because they

33:12.224 --> 33:15.327 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
cared and they put their
nose to the grindstone.

33:15.327 --> 33:22.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: But do
you think there should be a
specific race beat? And, if so,

33:22.133 --> 33:23.201 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
who should -- who
should have it?

33:23.201 --> 33:25.036 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

33:25.036 --> 33:27.205 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD PRINCE: You can have a
specific race beat, but you can
also make it everyone's

33:27.205 --> 33:30.175 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
responsibility.

33:30.175 --> 33:36.281 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And at another conference, Paul
Cheung, who is the head of the
Asian American Journalists

33:36.281 --> 33:41.119 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Association, he recommended
that, when you do these race
projects, you have -- you make

33:41.119 --> 33:46.992 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
them integrated, so that the
white journalists learn a lot
about what's going on in the
communities

33:46.992 --> 33:51.630 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of color, and they can learn
also from their colleagues of
color.

33:51.630 --> 33:57.002 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: So, when
you look at the landscape of
media today, how hopeful

33:57.002 --> 34:02.774 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are you that the media are going
to live up to your hopes and the
hopes of those journalists

34:02.774 --> 34:06.244 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of color and others who are
writing to you and complaining
that the media are not doing

34:06.244 --> 34:07.145 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
their job?

34:07.145 --> 34:09.247 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
RICHARD PRINCE: Right.

34:09.247 --> 34:15.220 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, I think that there is just
too much indifference to the
whole idea of diversity.

34:15.220 --> 34:20.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Yes, we will do it if we get to
it. I mean, the number of
newsrooms in this country that

34:20.659 --> 34:24.462 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have no people of color at all
in them is appalling. And the
fact that it's allowed

34:24.462 --> 34:29.567 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to remain, I think
is scandalous.

34:29.567 --> 34:36.775 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we're fighting apathy,
indifference and competing
interests. And people are
saying,

34:36.775 --> 34:41.246 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
look, I have to worry about the
bottom line. And they don't
realize that the bottom line

34:41.246 --> 34:45.650 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is tied to the changing -- our
changing country that's becoming
browner and browner. And that's

34:45.650 --> 34:49.187 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
where your potential
customers are.

34:49.187 --> 34:51.957 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so you better learn how to
relate to them if you want to
stay in business.

34:51.957 --> 34:53.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: But
after the Kerner Commission
report...

34:53.325 --> 34:55.593 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
RICHARD PRINCE: Yes.

34:55.593 --> 35:00.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: ...
newspapers, and then there were
only three networks, invested

35:00.865 --> 35:06.204 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in educating African-Americans
to live up to what the Kerner
Commission said. You need

35:06.204 --> 35:07.305 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
more people from
those communities.

35:07.305 --> 35:07.872 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
RICHARD PRINCE: Yes. Yes.

35:07.872 --> 35:09.708 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT:
Anybody doing that today?

35:09.708 --> 35:16.915 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD PRINCE: There are
internship programs at a lot of
the networks. Even FOX News has

35:16.915 --> 35:22.354 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an apprenticeship program for
people of color, something that
might surprise folks who think

35:22.354 --> 35:23.922 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of FOX News in a different way.

35:23.922 --> 35:25.991 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

35:25.991 --> 35:31.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD PRINCE: And FOX News
also has a separate Web site,
FOX News Latino, to reach
Hispanics,

35:31.563 --> 35:35.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
English-speaking Hispanics. And
that was just praised and got an
award from the National

35:35.633 --> 35:39.371 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
Association of
Hispanic Journalists.

35:39.371 --> 35:42.741 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, when -- when people see that
-- the business imperative, as
well as everything else, I

35:42.741 --> 35:45.243 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
mean, I think that's
when you get action.

35:45.243 --> 35:48.246 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: Well,
you're not as pessimistic as
some of the people you report

35:48.246 --> 35:50.181 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on, but, still, you say there
are things that need to be done.

35:50.181 --> 35:52.517 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So what are the solutions?

35:52.517 --> 35:56.454 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
RICHARD PRINCE: There are a
lot of other answers, too.

35:56.454 --> 36:02.594 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Like, the American Society of
News Editors has a program where
they go out into communities

36:02.594 --> 36:08.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and they interact with community
folks and they give them a
chance to talk to the media.

36:08.633 --> 36:14.806 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And there's a lot of
exchanges of ideas there.

36:14.806 --> 36:20.345 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The University of Missouri,
Mizzou, just said they were
going to have diversity -- a
diversity

36:20.345 --> 36:26.384 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
initiative required for all
students, faculty members and
staff members. This creates a

36:26.384 --> 36:32.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
climate so that, when people
actually do enter the work
force, they will be more aware
of

36:32.057 --> 36:38.396 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the need for inclusiveness and
the need for covering what needs
to be covered.

36:38.396 --> 36:42.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are a lot of solutions
that people are trying. And, as
people say, if one thing doesn't

36:42.033 --> 36:43.802 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
work, then you just
try something else.

36:43.802 --> 36:46.671 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHARLAYNE HUNTER-GAULT: Well,
Richard Prince, thank you.

36:46.671 --> 36:56.314 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
RICHARD PRINCE: Thank you.

36:56.314 --> 37:05.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: The historic climate
change accord in Paris is
expected to give a further boost

37:05.690 --> 37:09.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to wind, solar and other forms
of energy that are less
dependent on fossil fuels that
cause

37:09.227 --> 37:12.530 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
greenhouse gases.

37:12.530 --> 37:17.435 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Some observers think it will
change the business model for
energy in the decades to come.

37:17.435 --> 37:21.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when it comes to renewable
energy, there's a crucial
technological gap that is no
small

37:21.039 --> 37:22.674 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
hurdle.

37:22.674 --> 37:26.611 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Science correspondent Miles
O'Brien has our report.

37:26.611 --> 37:32.851 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: A hundred miles
north of Los Angeles, in
Tehachapi, California, the wind

37:32.851 --> 37:39.524 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
can be a bountiful resource,
but, unfortunately, not at the
right time. It blows hardest at

37:39.524 --> 37:43.428 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
night, spooling up these wind
turbines to their peak output,
when the demand for electricity

37:43.428 --> 37:45.864 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is at it lowest.

37:45.864 --> 37:51.870 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DOUG KIM, Southern California
Edison: So, matching the output
of wind to when customers

37:51.870 --> 37:55.073 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
really need it, that's certainly
one of the things that we're
looking at with this system

37:55.073 --> 37:57.742 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that you see here, because
you can store energy.

37:57.742 --> 38:02.747 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Doug Kim is the
director of advanced technology
for Southern California

38:02.747 --> 38:07.719 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Edison. The utility built this
eight megawatt lithium-ion
battery facility, designed to

38:07.719 --> 38:11.055 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
store electricity generated
by the turbines.

38:11.055 --> 38:17.028 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DOUG KIM: We can certainly use
this for an example, when the
wind blows during the nighttime,

38:17.028 --> 38:20.198 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
capture that energy during the
nighttime and then use it during
the daytime, when the demand

38:20.198 --> 38:22.200 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
is high.

38:22.200 --> 38:27.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The batteries,
stacked in racks here, are
equivalent to about 2,000
electric

38:27.572 --> 38:33.311 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
cars. It is the start of
Edison's effort to meet a
state-mandated requirement to
add 580

38:33.311 --> 38:37.582 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
megawatts of energy storage
into the grid by 2020.

38:37.582 --> 38:43.054 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's part of a big push to
invent ways to practically store
huge amounts of electricity,

38:43.054 --> 38:47.091 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so that renewables so can become
a more than fringe players on
the grid.

38:47.091 --> 38:49.460 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD SADOWAY, Massachusetts
Institute of Technology: If we
don't treat the intermittency

38:49.460 --> 38:55.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of renewables, they're --
they're not really a solution.

38:55.533 --> 39:02.473 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Electrochemist
Donald Sadoway is a professor at
MIT. He says lithium-ion

39:02.473 --> 39:07.946 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
batteries are not the answer;
they pose a serious fire risk,
and, as any laptop and

39:07.946 --> 39:13.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cell phone user knows, their
performance degrades fast as a
speeding Tesla. In short, they
are

39:13.551 --> 39:17.755 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
way too expensive and
impractical for widespread usage
on the grid.

39:17.755 --> 39:19.958 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But what are the alternatives?

39:19.958 --> 39:27.799 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD SADOWAY: The issue is
that we don't have a battery
technology that can meet the

39:27.799 --> 39:32.437 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
rigorous performance
requirements of the grid,
namely, super low-cost and super
long service

39:32.437 --> 39:34.872 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
lifetime.

39:34.872 --> 39:41.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Dr. Sadoway has
spent 30 years working in
electrometallurgy. So, no
surprise

39:41.746 --> 39:47.151 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that is where he found his
inspiration, specifically in the
aluminum smelting process.

39:47.151 --> 39:56.961 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD SADOWAY: So, an aluminum
smelter makes metal from dirt
for less than 50 cents a pound

39:56.961 --> 40:03.201 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and consumes huge quantities of
electricity. And I looked at
that and thought, man, if

40:03.201 --> 40:11.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I could take that thing and
teach it not to consume
electricity, but to store
electricity

40:11.075 --> 40:15.880 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and then to give it back on
demand, I know, at the end of
the day, it's going to be cheap.

40:15.880 --> 40:21.219 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: That was 10 years
ago. Today, Dr. Sadoway is on
the cusp of bringing a novel

40:21.219 --> 40:24.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
liquid battery to market through
a startup he founded called
Ambri.

40:24.956 --> 40:28.660 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DONALD SADOWAY: OK. So,
let's draw the battery.

40:28.660 --> 40:33.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Dr. Sadoway gave
me a chalk talk on how his
battery works. It is layered

40:33.865 --> 40:38.736 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
like a parfait, with a
low-density liquid metal at the
top, a high-density liquid metal

40:38.736 --> 40:42.774 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
at the bottom, and
molten salt in between.

40:42.774 --> 40:50.948 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD SADOWAY: And the way the
battery works is the metal on
the top wants to form a solution

40:50.948 --> 40:53.851 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
with the metal on the
bottom. We call it alloy.

40:53.851 --> 40:59.857 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: That interaction
creates a flow of ions,
electrical current. As it
discharges,

40:59.857 --> 41:04.929 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the top layer gets thinner and
thinner. When the sun is shining
on solar photovoltaic panels

41:04.929 --> 41:09.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
or the wind is spinning
turbines, the process is
reversed.

41:09.033 --> 41:15.707 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD SADOWAY: It reconstitutes
itself every time that it
recharges, which means that,

41:15.707 --> 41:23.815 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
unlike other batteries, which
will reduce their run time with
use, our battery just

41:23.815 --> 41:29.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
keeps on running. Show me
another battery that can do
that.

41:29.053 --> 41:32.557 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Actually, it
might be just few miles down
Massachusetts Avenue in a lab

41:32.557 --> 41:34.492 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
at Harvard.

41:34.492 --> 41:38.129 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MICHAEL AZIZ, Harvard
University: We took one of these
and we charged and discharged

41:38.129 --> 41:43.735 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it 700 times -- and if you think
about doing that once a day,
that's two years -- without

41:43.735 --> 41:46.738 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
any real sign of degradation
of the molecules.

41:46.738 --> 41:52.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Engineering
professor Michael Aziz is
developing a so-called flow
battery.

41:52.810 --> 41:58.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Flow batteries consist of two
separate tanks filled with
chemicals, one negative, one
positive.

41:58.416 --> 42:03.187 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The chemicals are pumped past
each other into the battery.

42:03.187 --> 42:08.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When wind turbines or solar
panels are generating power,
they charge the battery, pulling
electrons

42:08.693 --> 42:14.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from the positive, and pushing
them into the negative. When the
battery is turned on, the

42:14.232 --> 42:18.002 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
flow of electrons reverses,
generating electricity.

42:18.002 --> 42:23.775 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL AZIZ: The advantage of a
flow battery is, if you want
more energy, you just have

42:23.775 --> 42:30.481 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
bigger tanks of chemicals. And
that's possibly a much cheaper
way of getting the high amounts

42:30.481 --> 42:34.519 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of energy than stacking up
banks and banks of batteries.

42:34.519 --> 42:39.023 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Flow batteries
powered by a rare, expensive
metal called vanadium have

42:39.023 --> 42:43.428 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
been around for a while. But
Aziz is building his battery
with benign chemicals that are

42:43.428 --> 42:46.330 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
cheap and plentiful.

42:46.330 --> 42:50.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL AZIZ: They're organic
molecules. They're made of
carbon, hydrogen, oxygen,
earth-abundant

42:50.568 --> 42:53.604 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
elements like that, and they're
really very inexpensive.

42:53.604 --> 42:57.008 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Rhubarb.

42:57.008 --> 43:03.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL AZIZ: So, we noted in
our publication that the
molecule we're using is very,
very,

43:03.247 --> 43:06.717 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
very close to one
that's in rhubarb.

43:06.717 --> 43:10.955 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: So what on earth
could be cheaper than a rhubarb
battery? Maybe one that runs

43:10.955 --> 43:12.957 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
on air.

43:12.957 --> 43:16.127 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
DANIELLE FONG, Founder,
LightSail: This is version one.
Version -- this is it. This is

43:16.127 --> 43:21.132 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
version one. We -- the
technology, we're calling it,
regenerative air energy storage.

43:21.132 --> 43:26.604 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Danielle Fong was
all of 20 when she is co-founded
a Berkeley, California,

43:26.604 --> 43:32.844 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
startup called LightSail. Eight
years, and $70 million later,
the company has developed

43:32.844 --> 43:37.348 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a half-megawatt prototype system
that pumps air into a tank when
an intermittent power

43:37.348 --> 43:40.051 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
source is in operation.

43:40.051 --> 43:45.156 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DANIELLE FONG: By the time it
gets to the end, it's at 200
atmospheres. So that's, in

43:45.156 --> 43:51.729 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
units of pressure, 3,000 pounds
per square inch. It's really a
lot. When you want to

43:51.729 --> 43:57.635 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
get the energy back, you have a
valve open. As the piston is
drawing back, the valve closes,

43:57.635 --> 44:01.472 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and then the air expands, and it
drives the piston, which drives
the crankshaft, which

44:01.472 --> 44:06.210 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
drives a generator, which
produces AC power.

44:06.210 --> 44:11.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: LightSail is
developing lighter, cheaper
tanks made of composites to hold
the

44:11.349 --> 44:16.254 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
highly compressed air. Up until
now, the stumbling block for
this idea has been managing the

44:16.254 --> 44:22.460 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
heat. Air at high pressure
gets extremely hot.

44:22.460 --> 44:27.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LightSail's breakthrough idea?
Inject water droplets at the
perfect size into the
compression

44:27.331 --> 44:33.838 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
cylinder to cool the air.
LightSail says it's possible to
store all the power required to

44:33.838 --> 44:38.175 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
run an average American home for
a day, 30 kilowatt hours, in a
tank of compressed air

44:38.175 --> 44:41.078 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the size of a refrigerator.

44:41.078 --> 44:43.648 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DANIELLE FONG: There's more than
enough wind and more than enough
solar to handle everything

44:43.648 --> 44:46.651 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that we need. That's for sure.

44:46.651 --> 44:52.323 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the important question is,
how do we, in parallel, build
wind and solar resources

44:52.323 --> 44:56.727 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
along with energy storage, so
that there is the right amount
at every time? Right now,

44:56.727 --> 45:00.898 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I would argue there is sort of
like too much wind and solar,
and not enough storage.

45:00.898 --> 45:06.804 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Not even close.
And the task is large. Bill
Gates estimates all the
batteries

45:06.804 --> 45:12.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that currently exist in the
world could power global
electrical consumption for 10
minutes.

45:12.677 --> 45:18.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD SADOWAY: People know that
the battery is the missing
piece. Without a battery,
renewables

45:18.416 --> 45:20.818 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
are incomplete.

45:20.818 --> 45:26.257 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: But rising global
demand for electricity, along
with rising concern about

45:26.257 --> 45:31.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
climate change, may soon lead
researchers to the missing
puzzle piece, giving electricity

45:31.295 --> 45:34.765 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
some shelf life.

45:34.765 --> 45:47.712 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Miles O'Brien, the "PBS
NewsHour," Tehachapi,
California.

45:47.712 --> 45:57.888 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Actor Bill Murray is
enjoying a renaissance. He has a
new Netflix comedy

45:57.888 --> 46:01.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
special, and The New York Times
recently declared him a pop
culture icon.

46:01.392 --> 46:05.129 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It turns out Murray
is also a poet.

46:05.129 --> 46:09.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, as special correspondent
Francesca Maxime reports, he's
found a home at New York City's

46:09.033 --> 46:12.203 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Poets House.

46:12.203 --> 46:17.908 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DAN AYKROYD, Actor: I
think we better split up.

46:17.908 --> 46:19.310 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HAROLD RAMIS, Actor: Good idea.

46:19.310 --> 46:21.746 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BILL MURRAY, Actor: Yes. We
can do more damage that way.

46:21.746 --> 46:24.815 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRANCESCA MAXIME: This is the
Bill Murray we know, the actor,
the comedian, the one

46:24.815 --> 46:25.850 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
who makes us laugh.

46:25.850 --> 46:28.352 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BILL MURRAY: He slimed me.

46:28.352 --> 46:31.922 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRANCESCA MAXIME: But there's
also the Bill Murray we aren't
as familiar with, one who

46:31.922 --> 46:35.826 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
trades comedic lines for lines
of poetry at a yearly benefit
for Poets House.

46:35.826 --> 46:39.263 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BILL MURRAY: "What the Mirror
Said" by Lucille Clifton.

46:39.263 --> 46:52.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"Listen, you a wonder. You a
city of a woman. You got a
geography of your own. Listen,
somebody

46:52.076 --> 46:58.349 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
need a map to understand you.
Somebody need directions to move
around you."

46:58.349 --> 47:07.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I used to be able to look in the
mirror and see who's there. You
know, who's there? And,

47:07.024 --> 47:11.796 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sometimes, it's a reminder that
there's no one there at all.
There's not very much there.

47:11.796 --> 47:16.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, sometimes, there's someone
that gives me confidence.

47:16.600 --> 47:22.440 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I feel that that poem is
about someone who has an inner
-- you know, a self-confidence

47:22.440 --> 47:29.380 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that's bigger than -- that can't
be contained in the frame of a
mirror.

47:29.380 --> 47:33.350 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRANCESCA MAXIME: Murray loves
poetry so much, he wants to
share some of that confidence

47:33.350 --> 47:39.123 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
with poets, writers, and
readers. His support of Poets
House, a nonprofit library and
cultural

47:39.123 --> 47:43.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
center in New York City, has
helped make classes and writing
workshops like this one
possible.

47:43.894 --> 47:48.432 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: What we should be doing in
the poem is, like, thinking
about the way information is

47:48.432 --> 47:53.571 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
released at every step of the
way throughout the poem. Now,
how do we do that?

47:53.571 --> 47:57.641 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRANCESCA MAXIME: One way to do
that, according to Poets House
executive director Lee
Briccetti,

47:57.641 --> 48:02.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is having all kinds of poetry
available to read, for free,
under one roof.

48:02.379 --> 48:06.350 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LEE BRICCETTI, Executive
Director, Poets House: It is
really the national poetry
collection.

48:06.350 --> 48:12.957 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have collected, for the last
25 years, absolutely
comprehensively. You can walk in

48:12.957 --> 48:16.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and have an experience that
almost doesn't exist anymore,
especially doesn't exist for

48:16.861 --> 48:18.629 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
poetry.

48:18.629 --> 48:22.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRANCESCA MAXIME: Poets House
sits along the waterfront in
Lower Manhattan, boasting a

48:22.099 --> 48:28.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
60,000-volume public library,
exhibition space, reading room,
and children's room. Every year,

48:28.105 --> 48:32.543 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
it collects and displays
hundreds of books from
publishers in its annual
showcase, which

48:32.543 --> 48:36.781 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
assembles all American poetry
published in one year in one
place.

48:36.781 --> 48:40.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Still, some critics argue that
the location isn't gritty
enough.

48:40.417 --> 48:48.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LEE BRICCETTI: I have to say, we
were worried ourselves. And it's
more diverse. Our audiences

48:48.392 --> 48:54.098 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
have tripled. This is an
affluent community. And so we
really worked hard at making
sure

48:54.098 --> 49:00.171 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that our doors are open to
everyone, that we really make
sure that there are free class

49:00.171 --> 49:06.310 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
trips, and that we program in an
incredibly diverse way that
invites everyone in.

49:06.310 --> 49:10.314 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRANCESCA MAXIME: While Poets
House offers many in-house
programs, others take place

49:10.314 --> 49:14.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out in the community. We went to
their Poetry Walk across
Brooklyn Bridge this summer,
which

49:14.151 --> 49:17.922 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
is how Bill Murray first
encountered Poets House years
ago.

49:17.922 --> 49:22.526 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
While the Poetry Walk has been
going on for 20 years, it keeps
getting bigger and bigger

49:22.526 --> 49:27.464 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
every single year. This year,
hundreds of people came out in
order to hear Richard Blanco

49:27.464 --> 49:30.367 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
recite Walt Whitman's
"Crossing Brooklyn Ferry."

49:30.367 --> 49:36.173 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD BLANCO, Poet: "We love
you. There is perfection in you
also. You furnish your

49:36.173 --> 49:45.816 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
parts toward eternity. Great or
small, you furnish your parts
toward the soul."

49:45.816 --> 49:49.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRANCESCA MAXIME: At Poets
House, Oscar-nominated and
Pulitzer Prize-winning
screenwriters and

49:49.620 --> 49:54.258 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
poets rub elbows with everyday
visitors and fresh creative
writers like Aziza Barnes,

49:54.258 --> 49:56.760 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
who learned about Poets
House from a friend.

49:56.760 --> 50:00.497 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AZIZA BARNES, Poet: I would
start coming here, and I would
always run into somebody I loved

50:00.497 --> 50:05.102 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
here, like, no matter what. And
I was like, OK, I think this is
a rich place.

50:05.102 --> 50:10.207 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRANCESCA MAXIME: Barnes became
a Poets House emerging fellow in
2015. The fellowship included

50:10.207 --> 50:13.911 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a stipend and writing workshops,
with some of the country's
leading poets serving as

50:13.911 --> 50:17.281 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
mentors. There, she wrote the
poem entitled "Self-Portrait."

50:17.281 --> 50:24.288 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AZIZA BARNES: "Only the turn of
cement can arc black. I am blue
damage, mother-gut and

50:24.288 --> 50:33.464 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tower. Truth, we are all for
rent, red, lined systems. The
door out is green and full."

50:33.464 --> 50:36.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRANCESCA MAXIME: What was it
like being an emerging fellow
with a bunch of other young

50:36.133 --> 50:38.502 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
poets here at Poets House?

50:38.502 --> 50:44.375 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AZIZA BARNES: I think -- I think
that, especially in the class I
was in, there's, like, not

50:44.375 --> 50:48.579 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
really that much of an interest
in ego, in like I'm a good poet
because I wrote the thing

50:48.579 --> 50:51.248 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
